model.name: Kollarovic2016 - Cell fate decision at G1-S transition

body.div: Kollarovic2016 - Cell fate decision at G1-S transition

div.p: This model is described in the article:

div.a: To senesce or not to senesce: how primary human fibroblasts decide their cell fate after DNA damage.

div.div: Kollarovic G, Studencka M, Ivanova L, Lauenstein C, Heinze K, Lapytsko A, Talemi SR, Figueiredo AS, Schaber J.

div.p: Excessive DNA damage can induce an irreversible cell cycle arrest, called senescence, which is generally perceived as an important tumour-suppressor mechanism. However, it is unclear how cells decide whether to senesce or not after DNA damage. By combining experimental data with a parameterized mathematical model we elucidate this cell fate decision at the G1-S transition. Our model provides a quantitative and conceptually new understanding of how human fibroblasts decide whether DNA damage is beyond repair and senesce. Model and data imply that the G1-S transition is regulated by a bistable hysteresis switch with respect to Cdk2 activity, which in turn is controlled by the Cdk2/p21 ratio rather than cyclin abundance. We experimentally confirm the resulting predictions that to induce senescence i) in healthy cells both high initial and elevated background DNA damage are necessary and sufficient, and ii) in already damaged cells much lower additional DNA damage is sufficient. Our study provides a mechanistic explanation of a) how noise in protein abundances allows cells to overcome the G1-S arrest even with substantial DNA damage, potentially leading to neoplasia, and b) how accumulating DNA damage with age increasingly sensitizes cells for senescence.

p21 is also known as cyclin-dependent-kinase inhibitor 1

The model uses DNADamageC as a way to quantify DNA damage that can be repaired slowly. Slow repair is mainly attributed to cell cycle checkpoints. It is difficult to annotate this, as it is simply a way to quantify slowly repairable damage and is not a protein nor small molecule species. Thus, it is described with "isPropertyOf" double strand break sites and "hasProperty" DNA damage checkpoint.

The model uses DNADamageS as a way to quantify DNA damage that can be repaired quickly. Fast repair is not well elucidated but could be due to chromatin structure or DNA sequence context. It is difficult to annotate this, as it is simply a way to quantify quickly repairable damage and is not a protein nor small molecule species. Thus, it is described with "isPropertyOf" double strand break sites and "hasProperty" double strand break repair. While double strand break repair applies to both slow and fast repair, the distinction is made by applying cell cycle checkpoint repair to slowly repairable damage, DNADamageC above, and not to DNADamageS.
Total DNA damage is the sum of base DNA damage (BASE), slowly repairable damage (DNADamageC), quickly repairable damage (DNADamageS), and unrepairable telomere double strand breaks (TAF)

CycE is constitutively produced
CycE is constitutively degraded

The production of Cdk2 is consititutive in some versions of the model but negatively regulated by p21 in other versions. The "hasProperty: negative regulation of cyclin-dependent kinase activity" annotation is thus only relevant for versions of the model where this negative feedback aspect is included.

The degradation of Cdk is constitutive in some versions of the model but positively regulated by p21 in other versions. The "hasProperty: positive regulation of proteosome-mediated ubiquitin-dependent degradation" annotation is thus only relevant for versions of the model where p21 regulates the degradation process.
CycECdk2 complex association
Surprisingly, there were no more specific annotations for the dissociation of a cyclin-CDK complex.
CycECdk2 is activated by a CAK. The active form engages in a positive feedback loop, and the activation process can be inhibited by p21.
The CycECdk2 complex is deactivated by phosphorylation by Wee1.
